Fig. 5
 shows the Raman spectra of these FeNPs, but with different shells: EG/FeNP1141, Fol/EG/FeNP1141, and Pt/Fol/EG/FeNP1141 (15min reaction time). The three samples presented a similar Raman profile. As discussed in the previous paragraph, the maxima at 368, 492, 670 and 705cm−1 are associated with magnetite/maghemite. On the other hand, the interval between 1000 and 1700cm−1can serve to monitor organic contamination in these ferrofluids. Thus, Chourpa et al. [25] associated the peaks above 1000cm−1 in the Raman spectra of FeNPs with carbon contamination because this part of spectrum is often devoid of strong bands for ferrofluids that were freshly prepared in purified water. In contrast, these bands increased for samples kept at ambient conditions for 2weeks or more. This was also confirmed by the disappearance of the band at ca. 1580cm−1 after an additional wash of the ferrofluids with acetone. Additionally, Oblonsky et al. attributed the bands at 1105–1120cm−1 to short-chain saturated hydrocarbons [37]. In our case, when the EG/FeNP581 sample was dipped for 30 and 60min in a basic aqueous solution of folate (1mM), the intensity of the peak at 1560cm−1 increased (Fig. 6
). Folate adsorption to FeNPs increased the intensity of this peak, corroborating the proposals of Chourpa and Oblonsky.
